'''Friday''' is a day of the week. In some countries, for example the [[United States]], it is the sixth day of the [[week]]. In other parts of the world, for example the [[United Kingdom]], it is said to be the fifth day of the week.

In [[Christianity]], [[Good Friday]] is the Friday before [[Easter]]. It commemorates the [[crucifixion of Jesus]]. Special prayer services and ceremonies are held worldwide on this day with readings from the Gospel.

Friday is the [[Jumuah|Sabbath]] for [[Muslims]].

There is a [[superstition]] that a Friday on the [[13 (number)|13th day]] of a month is [[Triskaidekaphobia|unlucky]]. If the first day of a month is a [[Sunday]], the month will have a Friday the 13th. 

Some people consider Friday to be the last day of the week before the weekend. Others see Friday night as part of the weekend, since work or school is over for the week. In some places, the weekend is Friday and Saturday.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/11/23/johor-weekend-rest-day/ |title=Johor to have Friday, Saturday weekend rest days from Jan 1 |work=The Star |last=Tan |first=Christina |date=23 November 2013 |access-date=26 June 2019}}</ref> Because many people are happy to not have to go to work during the weekend, there are sayings like "Thank God it's Friday!".

Friday is named after Norse Goddess [[Frigg]].

